{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559484/1949031701/0106.xml":{"full_text":"Gore Graduates\nIn Engineering\nErnest Morrison Gore, son-in-law\nof Mr. and Mrs. George S. McCall\nof Marion, will receive his degree in\nElectrical Engineering at the Uni\nversity of Alabama today. This\nweek marks the end of the winter\nquarters and Gore is listed among\nthe outstanding graduates of the\n\"University. He is a member of Tau\nBeta Pi, National Engineering Fra\nternity.\nGore has accepted a position with\nthe Radio Corporation of America.\nHe will be with the RCA Victor di\nvision located at Camden, New Jer\nsey, beginning April 18.\nMrs. Gore will join him in Cam\nden when she completes her con\ntract with the University of Ala\nbama in June.\nSALT-SUBSTITUTE\nThe Food and Drug Administra\ntion has prohibited the sale of table\nsalt substitutes, following the death\nof at least four persons who used\nthe substitute. Food and Drug Com\nmissioner Paul B. Dunbar says the\nsale of Westal, Foodsal, Salti-sal\n.and other liquids containing lithium\n-chloride is strictly prohibited.\nThe 388 billion cigarettes produc\ned. in 1948 topped the 1947 record\nby 18 million.\nFor 33 Years Your Jeweler\nOnly Genuine Materials Used\nWork Guaranteed\u2014\nL. D. GREENE\nSouthern Railway\nWATCH INSPECTOR\nIMPROVE\nYOUR LAWN\nHave a lawn that's thick, deep\nrooted and beautiful. Vigoro\nprovides lawns with the nour\nishment they require for finest\ngrowth! Stop in for all your\nspring gardening needs and...\nA PRODUCT OF SWIFT\nJi meson's\nHARDWARE\nCross Mill Scouts\nRewarded For Work\ni\nBoy Scout Troop No. 4 met\nThursday evening at Cross Mill\nwith 28 of the 30 members and nine\ncommitteemen present.\nA. D. Greene, chairman of the\ncommittee; Wade Miller, Scout\nmaster, and Fred Murray, assistant\nScoutmaster, had charge of the\nmeeting.\nRefreshments were served the\nScouts by the committee as recog\nnition for their good work since the\nCourt of Honor last month. The re\ncord for the month included 33 ad\nvancements.\nRay Murray spoke on \"What A\nGood Scout Should Be,\" citing the\ndangers that arise as a result of\nnot occupying time in a worth\nwhile manner.\nOliver Cross made a group pic\nture of the boys and committee.\nCounty Council\nNames Committee\nThe County Council of Home\nDemonstration clubs meeting in th\u00ab\noffice of Miss Jean Steele, county\nagent, last Friday, discussed plans\nfor Achievement Day on October 8\nand Spring Federation on May 6.\nThe following committee was ap\npointed to plan the details of Achiev\nement Day: Mrs. W. M. Morgan, of\nGlenwood, Mrs. Finley Lonon, North\nCove, and Mrs. Tom Stacy, Nebo.\nThose present voted to serve din\nners in the office of the County Ag\nent as a means of raising money for j\ndepartment improvements.\nN. C. Got 4th Of Milk\nFrom Other States\nj\nRaleigh, March 11\u2014North Caro\nlina imported nearly one-fourth of\nits fluid milk supply from other stat-1\nes last year.\nC. W. Pegram, director of the\ndairy division of the State Depart\nment of Agriculture said the milk\ncost approximately $5,500,000.\nA report issued by Pegram based\non information from creameries and\ndistributors under the milk audit law\nshowed that wholesale milk purchas\nes from other states totaled 75,799,\n151 pounds in 1948 or 14,918,500\npounds more than 1947 imports of\n63,880,651 pounds.\nThe percentage of out-of-state\npurchases to the total fluid milk sup\nply was 25.5 per cent last year com\npared with 22.8 per cent the year\nbefore.\nPurchases of Grade A milk from\nNorth Carolina producers also in\ncreased last year, the report showed,\nwhile the quantity of ungraded or\n\"manufactured\" milk, used for con\nversion into other dairy products de\nclined.\nPegram interpreted this as indi\ncating that more and more North\nCarolina milk producers are \"real\nizing the wisdom of improving their\nfacilities so as to meet the State's\nstandards for Grade A milk.\"\nGLAMOUR SALAD\nThe next time you're making a\ncold meat salad and want a glamour\ntouch, add crushed pineapple, pine\napple chunks or Bing cherries.\nPenicillin is being tried experi\nmentally by some research institu\ntions as a possible means of com\ni batting some plant diseases.\nNOTICE OF MEETING\nThe Board of County Commissioners of McDowell\nCounty will sit as a\nBoard of Equalization and Review\nin the County Commissioners' Room in the Courthouse\nat 10 o'clock A. M., on the following days to hear any\ntaxpayer of the townships listed who has conplaint to\nmake in regard to assessment of property for taxes\nfor the year 1949:\nMONDAY, March 21, 1949\u2014 Crooked Creek\nMontford Cove\nNebo\nNorth Cove\nMONDAY, March 28, 1949\u2014 Old Fort, other than\nIndustrial and Com\nmercial properties\nTUESDAY, March 29, 1949\u2014 Marion, other than\nIndustrial and Com\nmercial properties\nDate for Industrial and Commercial hearing will be\nannounced lated.\nBOARD OF COUNTY COMMISSIONERS\n\nBy C. A. Workman, Chairman.\nCounties In\nMitchell District\nTo Receive $7,000\nCounties included in the Mt.\nMitchell District of the Pisgah Na\ntional Forest will receive more than\n$7,000 as their share from the sales\nof timber during the fiscal year\n1948, according to information re\ncently released by Carl G. Krueger,\nForest Supervisor.\nThat will be the pro-r^ted share\nof a $60,697.37 check recently sent\nto State Treasurer Branden Hodg\nes, according to word received from\nLyle Watts, Chief of the Forest Ser\nvice. The amount represents 25 per\ncent of the receipts from National\nForests within the state and dis\ntribution by counties is made on an\nacreage basis.\nOn that basis, distribution of the\nMt. Mitchell District share by\ncounties will be approximately as\nfollows: McDowell\u2014$4,023; Yan\ncey\u2014$2,104; and Mitchell\u2014$1,004.\nThese totals represent a considerable\nincrease over annual returns to\ndate and are due both to increased\nvolumes of production and an ad\nvance in timber prices.\nMacon county leads other North\nCarolina counties in the amount of\n1948 returns with $8,600. M'acon\nis within the Nantahala National\nForest. The leading county in the\nPisgah Forest is Transylvania which\nwill receive approximately $5,420.\nIn addition to the above amounts\nfrom the 25 per cent fund which is\nreturned to the counties through\nthe State treasury, another 10 per\ncent of forest receipts is returnable\nthrough the Forest Service admin\nistration for use in construction\nand maintenance of roads and trails.\nThus McDowell, Yancey, and Mit\nchell counties will benefit by an ad\nditional $2,350 through use of these\nfunds.\nAlthough timber demands are\nslow at this season and prices are\nreflecting these demands somewhat,\nRanger E. A. Heers has indicated\nthat current sales plans on his dis\ntrict promise little recession during\nthe coming year from this new re\ncord return.\nHome Demonstration\nClub Schedule\nThe March schedule of Home\nDemonstration club meetings has\nbeen announced by Miss Jean\nSteele, county agent, as follows:\nBethlehem: Thursday, March 17,\ntwo o'clock, lodge hall.\nWhite Pine: Thursday, March 17,\n7:30 y. m., home of Mrs. M. R.\nNanney.\nGreenlee: Friday, March 18, 7:30\np. m., home of Mrs. Edward Bur\ngin.\nTurkey Cove: Monday, March\n21, two o'clock, home of Mrs. Rus\nsell Hollifield.\nNebo: Tuesday, March 22, two\no'clock, home of Mrs. Watson Wil\nson.\nCherry Springs: Wednesday,\nMarch 23, two o'clock, home of\nMrs. Robert Pyatt.\nGlenwood: Thursday, March 24,\ntwo o'clock, school building.\nPleasant Gardens: Thursday,\nMarch 24, 7:30, home of Mrs. Fred\nConley.\nDysartsville: Friday, March 25,\ntwo o'clock, home of Mrs. Bruce\nCowan.\nChapel Hill: Tuesday, March 29,\ntwo o'clock, club house.\nj\nI North Cove: Wednesday, March\nj 30, two o'clock, school building.\nOld Fort: Thursday, March 31,\ntwo o'clock, home of Mrs. J. W.\n;Hogan.\nVehicle Total In\nN. C. Sets Record\nNorth Carolina Motor Vehicle\nRegistration in 1948 reached an all\ntime high of 956,451, the Motor Ve\nhicle Department in Raleigh has an\nnounced. This figure compares with\n883,498 vehicles registered in 1947.\nTabulation of vehicles in West\nern North Carolina counties are as\nj follows:\nAshe, 3,374; Avery, 2,082; Bun\ncombe, 28,140; Burke. 9,272; Cher\nokee, 2,643; Clay, 716; Graham,\n999; Haywood, 7,614; Henderson,\n17,973 and Jackson, 2,750.\nMicDowell, 4,386; Macon, 2,476;\nMadison, 2,981; Mitchell, 2,335;\nPolk, 2,505; Rutherford, 9,947;\nSwain, 1,217; Transylvania, 3,235;\nWatauga, 3,401 and Yancey, 1,801.\nLast year there were about two\nand a half billion goats in the Unit\ned States\u2014the smallest number in\nI 20 years.\nWhen tobacco was first taken\nfrom the United States to Europe,\njit was used as a narcotic.\nUse Of Certified\nSeed Recommended\nOnly by purchasing certified seed\ncan a farmer make certain that he is\ngetting the best product available,\nsays Dr. R. F. Moore, director in\ncharge of the North Carolina Crop\nImprovement Association at State\nCollege.\nDr. Moore says seed are unique in\nthat breeding cannot be determined\nfrom appearance alone. To deter\nmine in advance the type of crop\nwhich a particular lot of seed can\nproduce, it is necessary to know\nthe history of the seed and the con\ndition under which they were grown.\nIn the production of hybrid corn,\nthe plant breeder probably will\nknow much about the performance\nof the proposed hybrid before it is\nactually produced. After it is pro\nduced, it is put through a series of\nI tests to determine how its perform\nj ance compares with that of common\nly grown varieties or hybrids.\nThis type of information, Dr.\nMoore points out, is accumulated,\nsummarized, and made available for\nall growers who wish to take ad\nvantage of it. On open-formula hy\nbrids, similar information is avail\nable to reveal what the hybrid is,\nwhat it will do, and what it will not\ndo.\nFarmers wishing to take advan\ntage of this type of protection, says\nthe Crop Improvement directors,\nare urged to make use of certified\nseed.\nCOPPER PENNY POPULAR\nWashington\u2014The copper penny\nstill is the most popular coin in the\nUnited States.\nThe Bureau of the Mint plans to\ncoin 470,000,000 of them during\nthe next fiscal year, compared with\n135,000,000 nickles, 176,000,000\ndimes 53,000,000 quarters and 10,\n000,000 half dollars. The cost on\ncoinage ranges from $2.26 to coin\n1,000 pennies up to $12.19 to coin\n1,000 half dollars.\nOn January 1, farmers indicated\nthey planned to raise 25 per cent\nmore turkeys this year than last.\nTURN ABOUT\nMrs. Giddy\u2014I wonder' why those\ninquisitive people across the street\nare always looking into our win\ndow?\nMr. Giddy\u2014M.aybe, it's to find\nout why you are always looking\ninto theirs.\nPUMPKIN PUDDING\nEver thought of serving beef and\npumpkin together? An unsweetened\npumpkin custard with cubed leftov\ner beef makes a delicious main-dish\npudding.\nTw 9 Prr>f?rpss want ad.\nMASSAGIC tjtfil c&t<&/uon fJuceb\nI Yields wt\u00bbK every step\nit Absorbs iKmVv jars\nA Keeps you lool-l\u00abesh\nThe resilient air\ncushion and Arch\nLift built into Massagic\nShoes pave a smooth\npath to foot-comfort.\nCome here for a\nMassagic fitting.\nStyle 2532 De Luxe Quality\n\"Barrett's Lasti-Calf Widths\nB, C, D, E, EEE\u2014Sizes 6 to 12\u2014\n$13.95\nFEEL THE CUSHION\nI zz\nb\u00a3LK.6hOOfn\u00a3 CO.\nMARION, N. C.\nRabb Grocery\nFor Specials All Week\nBrisket Stew, 4 lbs. $1.00\nAmerican Cheese 41c lb.\nNUCOA\nPlain\nWholesome Vegetable Margarine\n32c lb.\nBreakfast Bacon 47c lb.\nJello, 2 packages for 15c\nBLUE PLATE\n\nStrawberry Preserves\nPINT\n38c\nTooth Paste, 50c size 39c\nChewing Gum, 3 for 10c\nBLUE PLATE\nMAYONNAISE\nMade by the Wesson Oil Company\nPint Jar 49c\n<Absolutely\n}ure Hfrd/i/ncooked\nPINT, 49c\nRabb Grocery Co.\nPhone 73 or 75 Free Delivery","height":"31172","width":"21344"}}
